04580nam a22006615i 9781477300213DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211982txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773002137 a10.7560/7601962doi  a(DE-B1597)588838  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aBUS0230002bisacsh1 aKaufman, Allen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCapitalism, Slavery, and Republican Values :bAmerican Political Economists, 1819-1848 /cAllen Kaufman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1982  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. ADAM SMITH on the Wealth of Nations and the Poverty of Labor -- t2. RICARDO and MALTHUS on Who Uses Labor Best, Capitalists or Landlords -- t3. DANIEL RAYMOND on Wealth without a Working Class -- t4. DANIEL RAYMOND on Protecting the Republic from Slave Capital -- t5. THOMAS RODERICK DEW on Accommodating the Republic to History -- t6. THOMAS RODERICK DEW on Black Slavery as the Republic's Check on the Working Class -- t7. JACOB N. CARDOZO on Making Slavery Work -- tAFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the troubled days before the American Civil War, both Northern protectionists and Southern free trade economists saw political economy as the key to understanding the natural laws on which every republican political order should be based. They believed that individual freedom was one such law of nature and that this freedom required a market economy in which citizens could freely pursue their particular economic interests and goals. But Northern and Southern thinkers alike feared that the pursuit of wealth in a market economy might lead to the replacement of the independent producer by the wage laborer. A worker without property is a potential rebel, and so the freedom and commerce that give birth to such a worker would seem to be incompatible with preserving the content citizenry necessary for a stable, republican political order. Around the resolution of this dilemma revolved the great debate on the desirability of slavery in this country. Northern protectionists argued that independent labor must be protected at the same time that capitalist development is encouraged. Southern free trade economists answered that the formation of a propertyless class is inevitable; to keep the nation from anarchy and rebellion, slavery—justified by racism—must be preserved at any cost. Battles of the economists such as these left little room for political compromise between North and South as the antebellum United States confronted the corrosive effects of capitalist development. And slavery's retardant effect on the Southern economy ultimately created a rift within the South between those who sought to make slavery more like capitalism and those who sought to make capitalism more like slavery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aFox-Genovese, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox-Genovese, Elizabeth.1 aGenovese, Eugene D.1 aGenovese, Eugene D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477300213423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477300213/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK